CIViC Description: While loss-of-function events in TP53 are very common in cancer, the R248 variants seem not only to result in loss of tumor-suppression, but also act as a gain-of-function mutation that can promote tumorigenesis in mouse models. This mutant is also more responsive to treatment with doxorubicin than its wild-type counterparts. While the prognostic impact of individual TP53 mutations is influenced by the cohort being studied, R248 mutations have been shown to confer worse overall survival. The R248Q mutation has also shown an increased invasive behavior in cell lines. This is specific to the 248Q variant.
